SIMPLE: wither
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wither
<hw>With"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Withered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Withering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wideren</ets>; probably the same word as <ets>wederen</ets> to
weather (see <er>Weather</er>, <pos>v.</pos> & <pos>n.</pos>); or cf. G.
<ets>verwittern</ets> to decay, to be weather-beaten, Lith.
<ets>vysti</ets> to wither.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To fade; to lose freshness; to become sapless; to
become sapless; to dry or shrivel up.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall he hot pull up the roots thereof, and cut off the fruit
thereof, that it <qex>wither</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Ezek. xvii.
9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lose or want animal moisture; to waste; to pin<?/
away, as animal bodies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is man, old, wrinkled, faded, <qex>withered</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was a man which had his hand <qex>withered</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now warm in love, now <qex>with'ring</qex> in the grave.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To lose vigor or power; to languish; to pass
away.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Names that must not <xex>wither</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>States thrive or <qex>wither</qex> as moons wax and wane.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wither</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wither
<hw>With"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to fade,
and become dry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun is no sooner risen with a burning heat, but it
<qex>withereth</qex> the grass, and the flower thereof falleth.</q>
<rj><qau>James i. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to shrink, wrinkle, or decay, for want of
animal moisture.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Age can not <er>wither</er> her.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shot forth pernicious fire⟦br⟧
Among the accursed, that <qex>withered</qex> all their strength.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to languish, perish, or pass away; to
blight; <as>as, a reputation <ex>withered</ex> by
calumny</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The passions and the cares that <qex>wither</qex> life.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Witherband</ent>⟦br⟧
